            <lb/>
Geology Lecture 1st 1805<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag1"
                ref="#misc_823"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag1">
          So different are the exertions of the faculties
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
of the mind, and so infinitely various the<lb/>
combinations of our ideas &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">that the same</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">objects</hi> may be examined with the most opposite<lb/>
views and considered under many diversified<lb/>
and beautiful relations.-<lb/>
It is on this fact of our nature so familiar<lb/>
to every understanding that the great extent <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of</del>
            <lb/>
and progression of science and philosophy depend -<lb/>
Hence their division into various branches and<lb/>
hence the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">distinguished</del> distinctness and<lb/>
accuracy of the different species of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Knowledge</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="4"
                xml:id="pb-4"
                facs="#i4"/>
            <lb/>
The Planet that we inhabit may be considered in<lb/>
its connection with the general system of<lb/>
the universe, as acted upon gravitation and<lb/>
revolving round the sun -<lb/>
It may be examined in the abode of<lb/>
organization and life covered with vegetables<lb/>
and peopled with animals, - or it may be<lb/>
studied as composed of different inorganic <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">parts</hi>
            <lb/>
variously arranged and subservient to different<lb/>
uses.-<lb/>
It is under this last point of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">view</hi> that it<lb/>
is the subject of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Geology</hi> - The Word is derived<lb/>
from <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the Greek language</hi> it signifies the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Science of the Earth</hi>, but its acceptation is<lb/>
limited and it is only <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">app</del> applied to<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">branch of Knowledge</hi> relating to<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="5"
                xml:id="pb-5"
                facs="#i5"/>
            <lb/>
The nature position and changes of the bodies<lb/>
that compose the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">known part</hi> of the surface<lb/>
of the Globe.<lb/>
The facts belonging to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Geology</hi> are numerous<lb/>
The objects of the study are as many as the<lb/>
substances found in our soils our Rocks and<lb/>
our Mountains in the Sea and in the Atmosphere<lb/>
And the alterations that those great parts<lb/>
of our system are continually undergoin<lb/>
can only be explained on the principles of<lb/>
this department of Philosophy.-<lb/>
The information to be derived from Geology<lb/>
is applicable to many purposes - In a number<lb/>
of instances it may be made subservient to the<lb/>
wants of life And all the theoretical views<lb/>
belonging to it when accurately pursued lead to<lb/>
beautiful <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">truths</hi>.-<lb/>
substances found in our <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">vain</unclear> our Rocks and<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="6"
                xml:id="pb-6"
                facs="#i6"/>
            <lb/>
Fixed <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">on the earth</hi> and dependent for our<lb/>
existance upon the various objects surrounding us<lb/>
Many of our necessities are supplied and some<lb/>
of our comforts produced by applications of<lb/>
the inorganic substances presented to us in<lb/>
Nature.-<lb/>
The soils from which we raise our vegetative<lb/>
nourishment the stones of which our habitations<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">are formed</hi> the fuel we employ for so many<lb/>
purposes and the metals <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">absolutely essential</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">to civilized Man</hi> are all subjects for the<lb/>
application <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of Geology</hi>
            <lb/>
And it is not merely <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">their nature</hi> which<lb/>
is indicated by this science but methods<lb/>
of discovering them and their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">extensive relations</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="7"
                xml:id="pb-7"
                facs="#i7"/>
            <lb/>
The rocks and stoney substances which are<lb/>
found beneath the soil, or which compose<lb/>
the foundations of our Hills though so various<lb/>
in their appearances yet contain many common<lb/>
substances.-<lb/>
The same bodies are found in very distant Countries<lb/>
There is an order in their position and the<lb/>
general nature of the mineral bodies belonging<lb/>
to a particular district, is in most cases<lb/>
indicated by the examination of a few<lb/>
specimens -<lb/>
In a mountainous country for instance<lb/>
if a stone of this nature occurs which is<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag2" ref="#chemical_092" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag2">
          Granite
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi> there is great reason to suppose<lb/>
that this <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">substance</hi> will be likewise <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">found</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
