The general usefulness <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of the Knowledge</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of Nature</hi> in increasing <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">mental enjoyment</hi>
            <lb/>
and in strengthening and exalting our<lb/>
sentiments -<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">But it</hi> surely will not be deemed improper<lb/>
to point out some of the peculiar<lb/>
intellectual effects of the objects of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">these</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Lectures </hi>and some of the advantages of<lb/>
the study as compared with that of other<lb/>
branches of science -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="15"
                xml:id="pb-15"
                facs="#i15"/>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of all</del>
            <lb/>
Of all the material objects which can employ<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">our attention those which are nearest to us</hi>
            <lb/>
ought to excite the warmest and the most<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">immediate interest</hi>.<lb/>
And after Man and animated Nature no<lb/>
subject of physical enquiry nears a more<lb/>
disinct relation to us than <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the place of</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">our abode</hi> the earth which is the cradle<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">our existance</hi> which affords the instrume<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">nts</add>
            <lb/>
of our power; and which thought not<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">great parent</hi> is the peaceful and<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">useful nurse</hi> of some of the most constant<lb/>
and uniform of our pleasures -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="16"
                xml:id="pb-16"
                facs="#i16"/>
            <lb/>
The study of the constitution of the Globe<lb/>
of the manner in which its changes are<lb/>
produced and of the laws by which dead<lb/>
and inorganic matter are rendered<lb/>
subservient to the purposes of living<lb/>
beings affords some of the most <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">sublime</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">objects</hi>which can ever occupy our<lb/>
contemplation.<lb/>
The are objects which even the most<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">insensible mind</hi> can scarcely consider without<lb/>
deep feeling -<lb/>
And they are capable of filling even the<lb/>
most comprehensive understanding and of<lb/>
calling forth the highest exertions<lb/>
of Genius.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="17"
                xml:id="pb-17"
                facs="#i17"/>
            <lb/>
The Rocks which are elevated in the<lb/>
clouds <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">or those</hi> which resist the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">waves of</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the sea</hi> their composition the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">laws of their</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">formation </hi>and their alterations in consequence<lb/>
of the action of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Atmosphere and of </hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">water</hi>these form only a part of the<lb/>
subjects of discussion of Geology -<lb/>
For this Science equally relates to the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Nature</hi> of soils <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <del rend="strikethrough">of all <add>the</add> solid</del>
            </add>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">strata of our Earth </del>
            <lb/>
of all the solid strata <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of our Earth</hi>
            <lb/>
to the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">gradual</hi>changes produced by the Ocean <lb/>
upon <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the land</hi> and to the great <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">convulsions</hi>
            <lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Nature</hi>occasioned by innundations, by Volcanoes<lb/>
and by <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Earthquakes</hi> -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="18"
                xml:id="pb-18"
                facs="#i18"/>
            <lb/>
The attainment of the Knowledge belonging to<lb/>
these highly interesting <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">subjects is found</hi>
            <lb/>
almost wholly upon <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">observation</hi>; for in a<lb/>
few cases only can instruments of experiment<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">be applied</hi>.<lb/>
And the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">acquaintance</hi> with mineral bodies<lb/>
which constitutes one of the most labourious<lb/>
and most interesting of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the study</hi> may in<lb/>
almost every case be derived from an<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">examination</hi> of their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">external characters.</hi>
            <lb/>
Geology perhaps more than any other departm<lb/>
of Natural Philosophy is a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">science</hi> of <lb/>
contemplation.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="19"
                xml:id="pb-19"
                facs="#i19"/>
            <lb/>
It requires no experience or complicated<lb/>
apparatus no minute processes upon the<lb/>
unknown properties of matter; It demands<lb/>
only an enquiring <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">mind</hi>; and senses alive<lb/>
to the facts almost every where presented<lb/>
in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Nature</hi>;<lb/>
And as it may be acquired without<lb/>
much difficulty so it may be improved<lb/>
without <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">much painful</hi> exertion -<lb/>
The person who is devoted to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Geological </hi>
            <lb/>
enquiries can scarcely ever want objects<lb/>
of employment and of interest.<lb/>
The ground on which He treads, the Country<lb/>
that <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">surround Him </hi>and even the Rocks<lb/>
and stones removed from their natural<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="20"
                xml:id="pb-20"
                facs="#i20"/>
            <lb/>
position by Art are all capable of<lb/>
affording him some degree of amusement<lb/>
and every new mine or Quarry that is<lb/>
opened every new surface of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the earth</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">is laid bare</hi> and every new Country <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">that</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">is discovered</hi> offers to him novel sources<lb/>
of information.<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">In</hi> travelling He is attracted to a pursuit<lb/>
which must constantly preserve his mind<lb/>
awake to the scenes presented to it.-<lb/>
And the beauty the Majesty and sublimity<lb/>
of the great forms of Nature have their<lb/>
effect in the imagination rather increased.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="21"
                xml:id="pb-21"
                facs="#i21"/>
            <lb/>
Than diminished by beings connected<lb/>
with the views of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Philosophy</hi> -<lb/>
The imagery of a Mountain Country<lb/>
which is the very theatre of the science<lb/>
is in almost all cass highly impressive<lb/>
and delightful but a new and a higher<lb/>
species of enjoyment arises in the mind<lb/>
when the arrangement in it, their harmony<lb/>
and its subserviency to the purposes<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of life are considered</hi>.<lb/>
To the Geological enquirer every<lb/>
mountain chain offers striking Monuments<lb/>
of the great alterations that the Globe<lb/>
has undergone.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="22"
                xml:id="pb-22"
                facs="#i22"/>
            <lb/>
The most sublime speculations are<lb/>
awakened, the present is disregarded<lb/>
past ages crowd upon the fancy and the<lb/>
the mind is lost in admiration of the<lb/>
designs of that great power who has<lb/>
established order in which at first view<lb/>
appears as confusion -<lb/>
It will not I trust be necessary to<lb/>
preserve these views to any greater extent.<lb/>
For sufficient I hope has been said<lb/>
to prove that the study is adapted to<lb/>
almost every mind and that any labour<lb/>
which may be bestowed upon it can<lb/>
scarcely be considered as vain.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="23"
                xml:id="pb-23"
                facs="#i23"/>
            <lb/>
A very few words will be sufficient to<lb/>
explain the plan which is my intention<lb/>
to adopt in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">develloping the principles</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of the Science</hi>, and in rendering them<lb/>
plain and intelligible.-<lb/>
As it may be supposed that some of my<lb/>
hearers are unacquainted with many of the<lb/>
terms belonging to Geology and as most<lb/>
of these terms will appear Barbarous and<lb/>
are really difficult to be rememberd, I shall<lb/>
introduce them as gradually as possible<lb/>
beginning with the History of the Science<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="24"
                xml:id="pb-24"
                facs="#i24"/>
            <lb/>
In this History the early opinions of the<lb/>
ancients concerning the elements of the<lb/>
Globe and their changes will first<lb/>
be discussed; and the more refined <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Theories </hi>
            <lb/>
of the Moderns which involve the outline<lb/>
of the science will be <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">afterwards </hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">considered</hi>, and in the general details<lb/>
the opinions that are complicated will<lb/>
follow those that are simple and distinct.<lb/>
After the History of the Science the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">general </hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">order </hi>of the facts belonging to it <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">will be explained </hi>
            <lb/>
the Nature of Rocks ans stones; and the relations<lb/>
of the different strata; and the changes that<lb/>
they are at present undergoing -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="25"
                xml:id="pb-25"
                facs="#i25"/>
            <lb/>
This part of the subject I shall illustrate as<lb/>
much as possible by large specimens by drawing <lb/>
and by picturesque sketches of the position of Rocks.<lb/>
From this last method much useful information<lb/>
it is my hope, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">may be derived</hi>.<lb/>
This painting will show the nature of the<lb/>
plan to be adopted.<lb/>
From the liberality of the Managers I shall<lb/>
be able to exhibit a number of the same kind<lb/>
and on the same scale and most of them<lb/>
will contain accurate portraits which will<lb/>
be the more interesting as belonging to the<lb/>
Island we inhabit.-<lb/>
After having examined the existing state<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the Globe</hi>
            <lb/>
The last subject of the course will be<lb/>
the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">description </del> discussion of the Theories<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="26"
                xml:id="pb-26"
                facs="#i26"/>
            <lb/>
that have been formed <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">to explain</hi> the<lb/>
Nature and position of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">its parts</hi>. The<lb/>
laws of their formation and the changes<lb/>
that they have undergone in the lapse<lb/>
of ages; and the principles and order<lb/>
by which the whole is continually preserved.<lb/>
It is this department of the science which<lb/>
will perhaps be <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the most interesting</hi>.<lb/>
It is the one that offers the greatest objects<lb/>
of contemplation - It has most employed<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">human ingenuity</hi>: and many of the Theories<lb/>
and speculations upon it exhibit brilliant<lb/>
examples of the most powerful <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">gen</del>
            <lb/>
efforts of Genius -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="27"
                xml:id="pb-27"
                facs="#i27"/>
            <lb/>
The task which I have preposed to my self in<lb/>
explaining all those various objects is one<lb/>
which in this Country I beleive has never<lb/>
been before <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">undertaken</hi> and it is one connected<lb/>
with much labour and with many difficulties -<lb/>
As yet no elementary treatise has been published<lb/>
on Geology I have been obliged to form any<lb/>
part of the arrangement and to collect the<lb/>
different facts from very distant and very<lb/>
scattered sources -<lb/>
It is a subject in which very few only<lb/>
of its parts will admit of the arrangement<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of language</hi> of beauty of description of elegance<lb/>
of expression. I shall spare no exertions to<lb/>
make it useful and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">intelligible</hi>:<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="28"
                xml:id="pb-28"
                facs="#i28"/>
            <lb/>
And in mentioning these circumstances<lb/>
I mean to apologise only for imperfections<lb/>
that cannot be avoided -<lb/>
The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">History of Geology</hi> is a subject<lb/>
that necessarily leads us to consider the state<lb/>
of the human mind even in the elder<lb/>
periods of time.<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Man</hi> in his most <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">savvage</del> savage must<lb/>
have been strongly impressed with the<lb/>
forms, appearances and changes of the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Earth and its diversified</hi> objects -<lb/>
And some of his earliest reasonings directed<lb/>
from effects to causes must have been connected<lb/>
with speculations on unknown times or <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">xxxxxx</unclear>
            <lb/>
alterations of matter and on the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">wonders of <del rend="strikethrough">Nature</del>
            </hi>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">creation</add>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="29"
                xml:id="pb-29"
                facs="#i29"/>
            <lb/>
In all the earliest systems of religions of the<lb/>
heathen Nations that have come down to the<lb/>
present times either by history or tradition<lb/>
certain doctrines are uniformly found relating<lb/>
to the formation of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Earth and its early</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">changes</hi> -<lb/>
And most of these doctrines appear to have<lb/>
been in some manner derived from the grand<lb/>
account of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">creation</hi> and of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">deluge</hi>
            <lb/>
delivered in the sacred writings -<lb/>
The cosmogony of the Hindoes offers a<lb/>
remarkable instance and is quoted as such<lb/>
by Sir W<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">m</hi> Jones from the account of the<lb/>
formation of the universe supposed to be given<lb/>
by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag27"
                ref="#misc_578"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag27">
          Manu the Son of Brama
        </term>
            </rs> to the Indian<lb/>
Sages.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="30"
                xml:id="pb-30"
                facs="#i30"/>
            <lb/>
            <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">D</unclear>
            <lb/>
The World, says He was all darkness undiscernible<lb/>
undistinguishable altogether as in a profound<lb/>
sleep still the self existing invisible God<lb/>
making it manifest with five elements and<lb/>
other glorious forms perfectly dispelled the<lb/>
gloom.<lb/>
He desiring to raise up various creatures<lb/>
by an emanation from his own glory first<lb/>
created the waters, and impressed them<lb/>
with a power of motion - by that power<lb/>
was produced a golden Egg blazing like a<lb/>
thousand Suns on which was borm <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag28"
                ref="#misc_577"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag28">
          Brama
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
self <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">ex</del> existing the greatest parent of all<lb/>
national beings.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="31"
                xml:id="pb-31"
                facs="#i31"/>
            <lb/>
