at Sais -<lb/>
From them <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag56"
                ref="#person_085"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag56" type="person">
          Plato
        </name>
            </rs> acknowledge that He<lb/>
borrowed the idea of the Atlantis fable<lb/>
and they are so very singular and contain<lb/>
so many opinions different from those<lb/>
of the Greeks concerning Nature and<lb/>
the changes <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of the Globe</hi> that I shall<lb/>
a translation of the most interesting part<lb/>
You Greeks says the Egyptian<lb/>
Philosopher to <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag57"
                ref="#person_760"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag57" type="person">
          Solon
        </name>
            </rs> -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="45"
                xml:id="pb-45"
                facs="#i45"/>
            <lb/>
You Greeks are always Children nor is<lb/>
there an experienced man amongst you -<lb/>
All your knowledge is lately acquired<lb/>
Neither containing any antient opinion<lb/>
derived from remote tradition nor any<lb/>
truth of ages that are long past.<lb/>
And the reason of this is the multitude<lb/>
and variety of the destructions of the human<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">race which</hi> have been <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">and which</hi> will be<lb/>
The greatest of these indeed arising from<lb/>
fire and water, but the lesser from ten<lb/>
thousand other contingencies.<lb/>
For the relations subsisting among you<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">that <del rend="strikethrough">Phae</del> Phaeton the ofspring </hi>of the<lb/>
sun <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">attempting to drive the Chariot </hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="46"
                xml:id="pb-46"
                facs="#i46"/>
            <lb/>
of his <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Father and not being able to</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">keep the track pointed out to him </hi>
            <lb/>
burnt up <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the substances</hi> belonging to<lb/>
the Earth and perished himself, blasted<lb/>
by thunder is indeed considered<lb/>
as fabulous: yet it is in reality true.<lb/>
For it expresses the mutations of the<lb/>
bodies revolving in the Heavens above<lb/>
the earth: and indicates that after<lb/>
long periods of time a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">destruction</hi>
            <lb/>
of terrestrial nature ensues from <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">devastation of fire</hi>.<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xxxxxxxxxx</unclear> those who dwell either on </del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Mountains or lofty <unclear>xxxxxxxx</unclear>
            </del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="47"
                xml:id="pb-47"
                facs="#i47"/>
            <lb/>
Hence those who dwell either on mounta<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ins</add>
            <lb/>
or  lofty and dry places perish more<lb/>
abundantly than such as dwell near<lb/>
rivers or on the borders of the sea<lb/>
To us indeed the hill is both salutary<lb/>
in this respect and in others and it preserves<lb/>
us from such devastations<lb/>
Again when the Gods purifying the<lb/>
Earth by water deluges its surface then<lb/>
the herdsmen and shepherds inhabiting<lb/>
the Mountains are preserved while the<lb/>
people of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">your</hi> cities are hurried away<lb/>
to the sea by the impetuous inundations<lb/>
of rivers.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="48"
                xml:id="pb-48"
                facs="#i48"/>
            <lb/>
On the contrary in our region neither<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">how</del> then nor at any other time did<lb/>
the water <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">descending from above pour</hi>
            <lb/>
with desolation on the plains but they<lb/>
naturally rise upwards from the bosom of<lb/>
the earth:<lb/>
And from these causes the most<lb/>
antient traditions are preserved in our<lb/>
country -<lb/>
Indeed it may be truly asserted that<lb/>
in the places where neither intense cold<lb/>
nor immoderate heat prevails the race<lb/>
of Mankind is always preserved. though<lb/>
sometimes the number of individuals is<lb/>
increased and sometimes diminished -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="49"
                xml:id="pb-49"
                facs="#i49"/>
            <lb/>
But what ever has been transacted<lb/>
either by us or by you or in any other<lb/>
place; beautiful or grand or wonderful<lb/>
is to be found in our temples preserved<lb/>
to the present day -<lb/>
While on the contrary you and other<lb/>
nations commit only recent transactions to<lb/>
writing and the other inventions which<lb/>
society has employed for transmitting<lb/>
information<lb/>
And hence when at stated periods of time<lb/>
these changes ordained by heaven as if diseases<lb/>
of nature destroys them among you who survive<lb/>
are both destitute of literary acquisitions and<lb/>
the inspiration of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag58"
                ref="#misc_011"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag58">
          the Muses
        </term>
            </rs> -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="50"
                xml:id="pb-50"
                facs="#i50"/>
            <lb/>
Hence it happens that you become<lb/>
again as it were an infant people<lb/>
and ignorant of the events which<lb/>
happened in ancient times whether in<lb/>
foreign lands or in your own <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Country</hi>
            <lb/>
Of the Grecian Philosophers <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
